1
00:00:00,391 --> 00:00:01,991
<i>Previously on</i> Jericho

2
00:00:02,291 --> 00:00:03,591
Some of them were on planes

3
00:00:03,691 --> 00:00:05,191
that landed in the middle of nowhere.

4
00:00:05,691 --> 00:00:06,991
They've been walking for weeks.

5
00:00:07,591 --> 00:00:09,091
They must have gone through hell.

6
00:00:09,491 --> 00:00:10,491
Oh, my God.

7
00:00:12,491 --> 00:00:14,391
At the current levels of consumption,

8
00:00:14,491 --> 00:00:17,790
we will be completely
out of gas and diesel in two weeks.

9
00:00:17,791 --> 00:00:19,790
There's a woman in that
group of refugees that

10
00:00:19,791 --> 00:00:21,991
Bill is processing.
I think you should talk to her.

11
00:00:22,591 --> 00:00:23,591
Hello, Rob.

12
00:00:23,791 --> 00:00:25,890
Someone on my team sold us all out.

13
00:00:25,891 --> 00:00:26,990
You're smart enough to know

14
00:00:26,991 --> 00:00:29,391
that they would say anything
to get you to talk, Sarah.

15
00:00:30,591 --> 00:00:32,391
Get the package.

16
00:00:44,691 --> 00:00:46,091
We're the United States Marines,

17
00:00:46,391 --> 00:00:47,491
and we're here to help.

18
00:00:47,891 --> 00:00:49,490
... and those are to restore lights,

19
00:00:49,491 --> 00:00:52,891
power and infrastructure
to Kansas, one town at a time.

20
00:00:57,190 --> 00:00:59,390
Something's wrong about all this,
all right? Trust me.

21
00:00:59,391 --> 00:01:02,532
They've got somebody on the edge of town
pretending to be their headquarters.

22
00:01:02,791 --> 00:01:03,991
Is any of this real?

23
00:01:04,191 --> 00:01:06,390
- The gun's real.
- Hands up. Get them up!

24
00:01:06,391 --> 00:01:07,891
What the hell do we do with them?

25
00:01:08,091 --> 00:01:09,891
You will leave your weapons on the tank,

26
00:01:10,191 --> 00:01:11,391
and you will move out!

27
00:01:11,491 --> 00:01:13,091
- What do we do with that?
- Stanley,

28
00:01:13,491 --> 00:01:14,491
got room in your barn?

29
00:01:14,591 --> 00:01:16,391
- Seriously?
- Why not?

30
00:01:17,791 --> 00:01:19,391
Never know when you might need a tank.

31
00:01:47,591 --> 00:01:49,291
You're making too much noise.

32
00:01:49,391 --> 00:01:50,491
Sorry.

33
00:01:51,691 --> 00:01:52,691
Where did it go?

34
00:01:54,991 --> 00:01:55,991
There it is.

35
00:02:06,891 --> 00:02:08,891
- It's locked.
- We shouldn't go in.

36
00:02:12,891 --> 00:02:13,891
Go in here.

37
00:02:13,991 --> 00:02:16,091
- Why do I have to?
- So we can eat.

38
00:02:26,091 --> 00:02:27,091
You see it?

39
00:02:28,391 --> 00:02:29,391
Katie?

40
00:02:39,991 --> 00:02:41,491
<i>Come on, Jake,
there's a line here.

41
00:02:41,591 --> 00:02:42,891
<i>Did you hear about the tank?

42
00:02:43,091 --> 00:02:44,491
<i>Those Marines coming or what?

43
00:02:44,591 --> 00:02:47,391
<i>Everybody, just calm down!
You'll get your share.

44
00:02:49,391 --> 00:02:50,791
<i>You'll get your rations!

45
00:02:51,491 --> 00:02:53,291
<i>People, please, back up!

46
00:02:54,691 --> 00:02:55,991
How is Gray handling this?

47
00:02:56,057 --> 00:02:57,090
You better get in there.

48
00:02:57,091 --> 00:02:59,091
I think we really screwed
ourselves this time.

49
00:02:59,191 --> 00:03:02,490
You said everyone in the shelter gets
half-rations until the Marines come.

50
00:03:02,491 --> 00:03:04,991
Well, the Marines aren't coming,
and you've known all along.

51
00:03:05,191 --> 00:03:06,891
We did the best that we could.

52
00:03:06,964 --> 00:03:08,890
People had to believe
that help was on the way.

53
00:03:08,891 --> 00:03:09,990
And you know what?

54
00:03:09,991 --> 00:03:13,091
Half-rations is a lot more than
those refugees had before they got here.

55
00:03:13,791 --> 00:03:14,891
Did you know about this?

56
00:03:15,091 --> 00:03:16,891
The Marines...
That they were con artists?

57
00:03:18,291 --> 00:03:20,591
Yeah, but we didn't give them
any of our supplies.

58
00:03:20,691 --> 00:03:23,591
And Gray is right. The last thing
this town needs is to lose hope.

59
00:03:23,991 --> 00:03:26,091
Hope won't keep
my friends from starving.

60
00:03:26,291 --> 00:03:28,691
I've got one woman too weak to walk.

61
00:03:28,791 --> 00:03:30,191
It's a mathematical problem.

62
00:03:30,391 --> 00:03:32,790
We've got your friends,
plus another 50 who migrated here.

63
00:03:32,791 --> 00:03:34,791
That's too many people,
and not enough food.

64
00:03:34,891 --> 00:03:37,341
We'll just have to figure out
how to make what we have last.

65
00:03:37,391 --> 00:03:38,891
I say the first thing we do,

66
00:03:38,991 --> 00:03:40,791
is stop giving it away to strangers.

67
00:04:26,791 --> 00:04:29,491
What if we cut
the food rations in half,

68
00:04:29,791 --> 00:04:30,791
again?

69
00:04:31,140 --> 00:04:32,990
It's more than the food.
What about medicine?

70
00:04:32,991 --> 00:04:34,207
Those refugees came here sick.

71
00:04:34,240 --> 00:04:36,290
They've been burning through
our meds for a month.

72
00:04:36,291 --> 00:04:38,091
Can we make it to spring, Harry?

73
00:04:38,691 --> 00:04:40,091
Some of us can. Not all.

74
00:04:41,091 --> 00:04:42,891
Crime's been going up
since they got here.

75
00:04:42,991 --> 00:04:44,690
Crime's been going up
since the bombs.

76
00:04:44,691 --> 00:04:47,191
It's got to be done.
The numbers speak for themselves.

77
00:04:47,291 --> 00:04:48,090
Just look at 'em.

78
00:04:48,123 --> 00:04:50,291
I don't need to look at 'em.
I see them in my sleep.

79
00:04:52,191 --> 00:04:53,191
What are you going to do?

80
00:04:56,691 --> 00:04:57,691
Folks?

81
00:04:57,791 --> 00:04:58,791
Folks, listen up!

82
00:04:59,891 --> 00:05:01,690
I am sorry to say that

83
00:05:01,691 --> 00:05:04,991
the town no longer has the resources
to take care of you.

84
00:05:05,391 --> 00:05:06,991
<i>What?
Where are we supposed to go?

85
00:05:07,791 --> 00:05:10,490
So if you could please
gather up your belongings,

86
00:05:10,491 --> 00:05:12,890
you will be escorted
to a FEMA camp out

87
00:05:12,891 --> 00:05:15,391
- near I-70.
- We've been to those FEMA camps.

88
00:05:16,191 --> 00:05:17,991
We barely made it out
alive the first time.

89
00:05:18,591 --> 00:05:22,191
FEMA has medicine and supplies,
and we don't.

90
00:05:22,391 --> 00:05:23,891
You heard the mayor.

91
00:05:24,791 --> 00:05:25,991
You need to start packing up.

92
00:05:26,591 --> 00:05:28,391
What are you going to do,
put us in jail?

93
00:05:28,591 --> 00:05:29,591
Great.

94
00:05:30,291 --> 00:05:31,591
If I didn't have to do this,

95
00:05:32,091 --> 00:05:33,991
- I wouldn't.
- We've been working!

96
00:05:34,291 --> 00:05:36,391
Okay? We've been chopping wood!

97
00:05:36,491 --> 00:05:38,891
Jessica's been helping you
with your medical center.

98
00:05:41,891 --> 00:05:42,891
I'm sorry.

99
00:05:43,091 --> 00:05:44,491
But if you put us out on the...

100
00:05:45,291 --> 00:05:46,591
This isn't a debate.

101
00:05:50,291 --> 00:05:51,291
You're right.

102
00:05:51,691 --> 00:05:52,791
'Cause we're staying.

103
